Scott: World's Blankiest Blank.

465
00:27:04,950 --> 00:27:12,790
Scott: We're going to do today's show on the history and whatnot of P2P file sharing thingies.

466
00:27:13,110 --> 00:27:21,250
Rym: Yeah, a few people have asked about it and all the other topics you've asked about, we kind of went long in the news, so we don't want to spend a short episode on something big.

467
00:27:21,510 --> 00:27:29,750
Scott: Yeah, we're not going to get too technical into exactly how they work or how you can use them or copyright or anything like that.

468
00:27:30,050 --> 00:27:35,183
Scott: We're just going to talk about the history of P2P usage in general, the major networks, etc.

469
00:27:37,870 --> 00:27:45,990
Rym: Yeah, because basically the two of us, we're from the generation that lived through the dawn of the MP3 age, like directly.

470
00:27:46,430 --> 00:27:49,910
Rym: We got some of the first MP3s and we were along at every step of the way.

471
00:27:50,990 --> 00:28:03,170
Rym: And it startled me one day when someone at my work was talking about Napster and they had no idea that Napster used to be the thing, because they've only known Napster as that crappy Napster what it is today.

472
00:28:03,450 --> 00:28:03,855
Scott: Really?

473
00:28:03,916 --> 00:28:05,010
Scott: Wow, that wasn't until recently.

474
00:28:05,492 --> 00:28:09,806
Rym: Yeah, well, people who really weren't hip with it, or people who were young, or people who didn't care, don't really know.

475
00:28:09,827 --> 00:28:10,669
Rym: And it's kind of fascinating.

476
00:28:10,830 --> 00:28:13,410
Scott: But it was all over the news back in the day when it was for real.

477
00:28:13,730 --> 00:28:16,070
Rym: They didn't know what it was, or they didn't pay attention.

478
00:28:16,670 --> 00:28:20,770
Scott: Okay, well, in the beginning there was two things.

479
00:28:20,850 --> 00:28:22,050
Rym: Well, in the beginning there was MIDI.

480
00:28:22,791 --> 00:28:25,395
Rym: Well, okay.

481
00:28:27,038 --> 00:28:28,540
Scott: MIDI files were the beginning.

482
00:28:28,780 --> 00:28:32,907
Scott: You could get them from websites, and Usenets, and IRCs, and FTPs.

483
00:28:35,150 --> 00:28:36,875
Scott: That was the beginning of those four things.

484
00:28:37,036 --> 00:28:40,667
Scott: Usenet, IRC, FTP, websites.

485
00:28:40,907 --> 00:28:41,730
Scott: One, two, three, four.

486
00:28:42,931 --> 00:28:49,430
Rym: Now, before Napster and peer-to-peer and all that, basically the only way to get MP3s, which were this elite thing.

487
00:28:49,570 --> 00:28:53,628
Rym: I mean, they were, in that day, like Where's was in the late 80s, early 90s.

488
00:28:54,490 --> 00:28:59,430
Rym: It was the thing that people would collect and seek out, and parter over, and fight with, and it was fun.

489
00:28:59,750 --> 00:29:00,993
Scott: Yeah, there would be trades.

490
00:29:01,594 --> 00:29:06,564
Scott: They'd be like, "Hey, I'll wait the 20 minutes it takes to send this to you.

491
00:29:06,664 --> 00:29:08,869
Scott: if you wait the 20 minutes it takes to send that to

492
00:29:08,909 --> 00:29:09,009
Scott: me.".

493
00:29:09,791 --> 00:29:17,290
Rym: Or there were just blatant FTP sites where you'd log in, and they had ratios where for every 10 megabytes you uploaded, you were allowed to download one megabyte.

494
00:29:17,630 --> 00:29:25,190
Scott: Yeah, a lot of IRC channels would have bots in them, and you could send files to the bots, and then they would send you things back.

495
00:29:25,550 --> 00:29:29,980
Rym: And of course there were the MP3 sites, which would have thousands of links.

496
00:29:30,462 --> 00:29:33,970
Rym: Maybe five of them would work, but you'd click on every goddamn one.

497
00:29:34,570 --> 00:29:36,709
Rym: You didn't care what the song was, you'd download it.

498
00:29:36,950 --> 00:29:37,650
Scott: That's right.

499
00:29:38,094 --> 00:29:39,989
Rym: I got some shitty music because of that.

500
00:29:40,970 --> 00:29:48,070
Scott: I think I got one song that way, ever, because I just didn't care, and then I forgot to, what, you had to burn it or something?

501
00:29:48,190 --> 00:29:49,082
Rym: Oh, you had to uh...

502
00:29:49,670 --> 00:29:50,014
Scott: Scrape it?

503
00:29:50,420 --> 00:29:50,947
Scott: What was the word?

504
00:29:51,290 --> 00:29:52,820
Rym: It was MP3 cooked.

505
00:29:52,900 --> 00:29:54,027
Rym: You had to uncook MP3s.

506
00:29:54,730 --> 00:29:54,819
Scott: Yup.

507
00:29:55,290 --> 00:30:02,550
Rym: Because back then, no one, no web server was set up to let you download MP3s, binary files.

508
00:30:03,153 --> 00:30:06,290
Rym: So it wouldn't know mime types, it would just download ASCII.

509
00:30:06,970 --> 00:30:13,770
Rym: So you'd get an MP3, you'd go to play it, and instead of music coming out, the godawful screeches of the damned would come out of your speakers.

510
00:30:14,250 --> 00:30:14,945
Scott: Yup, yup.

511
00:30:15,952 --> 00:30:20,610
Scott: The only way to fix it was- And Winamp would use your 100% CPU usage on your 486.

512
00:30:20,610 --> 00:30:21,191
Rym: Yup, yup.

513
00:30:21,712 --> 00:30:29,530
Rym: Or because you had an ISA sound card and an ISA network card, you couldn't play MP3s and download websites at the same time.

514
00:30:29,890 --> 00:30:29,980
Rym: Yup.

515
00:30:30,832 --> 00:30:32,970
Rym: But one day, Napster appeared.

516
00:30:34,110 --> 00:30:34,949
Scott: Napster was god.

517
00:30:35,490 --> 00:30:39,410
Rym: Now when it first appeared, there was about a two week period where I didn't know anything about it.

518
00:30:39,650 --> 00:30:41,718
Rym: Like I heard of it, and I thought it was something stupid.

519
00:30:41,738 --> 00:30:44,910
Rym: I thought it was like MP3 sites, but for the masses.

520
00:30:45,210 --> 00:30:50,370
Scott: I heard the word Napster, I didn't know what it was, one day eventually I got around to using it, and holy crap.

521
00:30:50,871 --> 00:30:59,209
Rym: Well one day in high school, this girl was sitting there and she said, "Napster is great, but half the songs I get don't sound right and it takes forever to download

522
00:30:59,229 --> 00:30:59,350
Rym: them.".

523
00:31:00,254 --> 00:31:01,882
Rym: And I said, "Why are you using Napster?

524
00:31:01,983 --> 00:31:02,847
Rym: Just go to FTP

525
00:31:02,887 --> 00:31:03,209
Rym: sites.".

526
00:31:04,592 --> 00:31:05,541
Rym: Then I got home and I thought,

527
00:31:05,944 --> 00:31:06,186
Rym: "Huh.".

528
00:31:06,650 --> 00:31:09,730
Rym: So I went on Yahoo, because back then that was what you searched with.

529
00:31:09,770 --> 00:31:10,759
Scott: There was no Google then.

530
00:31:10,779 --> 00:31:11,687
Scott: No Google.

531
00:31:12,110 --> 00:31:16,629
Rym: I typed "Napster" and I saw this website, and I wasn't sure what to make of it.

532
00:31:18,171 --> 00:31:20,890
Scott: Well, there was this protocol that they invented called OpenNAP.

533
00:31:21,450 --> 00:31:22,869
Scott: Well, I don't think it was called OpenNAP.

534
00:31:23,151 --> 00:31:24,301
Rym: It was called Napster.

535
00:31:24,402 --> 00:31:25,210
Scott: It was called Napster.

536
00:31:25,230 --> 00:31:25,666
Scott: Something like that.

537
00:31:26,450 --> 00:31:29,830
Scott: Basically what it was, is you would run a server, which is a Napster server.

538
00:31:30,290 --> 00:31:34,570
Scott: So it was still sort of a client server deal, which is how they were able to shut it down in the first place.

539
00:31:35,290 --> 00:31:41,210
Scott: And the server had an IRC, and it let you chat with other people, and it let you send files to other people.

540
00:31:41,812 --> 00:31:46,467
Scott: And you could say, "These are the files that I am sharing," or, "These are the directories I am

541
00:31:46,527 --> 00:31:46,908
Scott: sharing.".

542
00:31:47,591 --> 00:31:56,150
Scott: And people could search, and based on file names they could come up with files that other people were sharing, and directly download them from other people.

543
00:31:56,230 --> 00:32:04,385
Scott: And you could say, "I will allow X people to download from me at once," and, "I will allow one person to download these many things from me at a

544
00:32:04,425 --> 00:32:04,987
Scott: time.".

545
00:32:05,971 --> 00:32:09,470
Rym: Now, it was very primitive compared to the peer-to-peer you're used to today.

546
00:32:09,870 --> 00:32:10,530
Scott: Very primitive.

547
00:32:10,530 --> 00:32:12,076
Rym: You had to do everything manually.

548
00:32:12,297 --> 00:32:15,310
Rym: You'd find ten people who had the file you wanted.

549
00:32:15,610 --> 00:32:17,710
Rym: You picked the guy who was probably the fastest.

550
00:32:18,450 --> 00:32:19,518
Scott: And you couldn't just say, "Get from

551
00:32:19,579 --> 00:32:19,881
Scott: everyone."

552
00:32:19,901 --> 00:32:20,446
Scott: You picked one guy.

553
00:32:22,890 --> 00:32:27,070
Rym: Now, searching was great, because most stuff was on there, unless you listened to any good music.

554
00:32:28,030 --> 00:32:28,371
Scott: Well, no.

555
00:32:28,812 --> 00:32:34,329
Scott: The thing about Napster was that even though it was so primitive, so many people were using it.

556
00:32:35,194 --> 00:32:36,149
Rym: Because there was no fear.

557
00:32:37,112 --> 00:32:37,474
Scott: Well, no.

558
00:32:37,514 --> 00:32:38,620
Scott: It's not that there was no fear.

559
00:32:38,660 --> 00:32:40,330
Scott: It's that you could find anything.

560
00:32:41,010 --> 00:32:45,130
Scott: Because it was like the library of Alexandria when it comes to music and file sharing.

561
00:32:45,650 --> 00:32:47,590
Scott: Everything you could think of was there somewhere.

562
00:32:47,670 --> 00:32:49,390
Rym: Well, anything you could think of that was modern.

563
00:32:50,053 --> 00:32:50,326
Scott: Oh, yeah.

564
00:32:50,510 --> 00:32:51,698
Rym: You couldn't find old stuff.

565
00:32:51,879 --> 00:32:53,710
Rym: You couldn't find a lot of foreign stuff right away.

566
00:32:53,870 --> 00:32:59,630
Scott: You couldn't find old and foreign stuff, but anything that was ever really on the radio in America, you could find.

567
00:33:00,251 --> 00:33:00,475
Rym: Yeah.

568
00:33:00,496 --> 00:33:00,964
Rym: And really...

569
00:33:01,330 --> 00:33:02,637
Scott: Type in Elvis, every Elvis song.

570
00:33:02,698 --> 00:33:04,970
Scott: Type in Rolling Stones, every Rolling Stones song.

571
00:33:05,011 --> 00:33:05,460
Scott: Just ding!

572
00:33:05,521 --> 00:33:05,889
Scott: There they are.

573
00:33:06,150 --> 00:33:09,730
Rym: And no one really thought about it, because no one was being sued.

574
00:33:10,172 --> 00:33:12,610
Rym: Most people who used it didn't even think about it being illegal.

575
00:33:13,270 --> 00:33:15,410
Rym: Especially since it was from this legit-looking company.

576
00:33:16,130 --> 00:33:17,318
Scott: Yeah, people just did it.

577
00:33:17,499 --> 00:33:18,345
Scott: Everyone was happy.

578
00:33:18,405 --> 00:33:19,150
Scott: Everything was awesome.

579
00:33:19,290 --> 00:33:22,230
Scott: At college campuses, it was insane, because everything was so fast.

580
00:33:22,390 --> 00:33:23,200
Scott: You'd be like, "Song!

581
00:33:23,241 --> 00:33:23,464
Scott: Song!

582
00:33:23,484 --> 00:33:23,707
Scott: Song!

583
00:33:23,727 --> 00:33:23,848
Scott: Song!".

584
00:33:23,970 --> 00:33:28,170
Scott: And within a minute, everyone on the whole campus could have every single thing everyone else had.

585
00:33:28,633 --> 00:33:29,250
Scott: It was crazy.

586
00:33:29,750 --> 00:33:29,892
Rym: Yep.

587
00:33:30,013 --> 00:33:31,410
Rym: And it ushered in a new era.

588
00:33:31,650 --> 00:33:34,550
Rym: My MP3 collection quintupled every day.

589
00:33:34,791 --> 00:33:35,714
Scott: It was the greatest.

590
00:33:36,577 --> 00:33:36,999
Scott: Absolutely.

591
00:33:37,019 --> 00:33:40,470
Scott: But then freshman year of college is, what, 2000?

592
00:33:40,470 --> 00:33:40,605
Rym: Yeah.

593
00:33:41,511 --> 00:33:41,932
Scott: 2001-ish.

594
00:33:42,635 --> 00:33:47,410
Scott: They started to block it and filter it, and eventually they killed it off pretty quick.

595
00:33:47,690 --> 00:33:49,329
Rym: Yeah, then it got sued and it went down.

596
00:33:50,130 --> 00:33:50,608
Scott: Which sucked.

597
00:33:51,350 --> 00:33:51,793
Rym: Of course.

598
00:33:51,813 --> 00:33:55,150
Rym: Right about that time, the peer-to-peer revolution happened.

599
00:33:55,290 --> 00:33:57,022
Rym: Because Napster itself wasn't that great.

600
00:33:57,103 --> 00:33:58,069
Rym: It was just the first one.

601
00:33:58,491 --> 00:34:04,950
Scott: Well, there was other ones that were about what Napster was about, but none of them had the people to actually be useful.

602
00:34:05,330 --> 00:34:10,050
Rym: Well, because Napster came, it was the first one that took off, and the community was so big that that was it.

603
00:34:10,130 --> 00:34:11,248
Rym: You didn't need to go anywhere else.

604
00:34:12,532 --> 00:34:14,270
Rym: Of course, as time went on, other ones appeared.

605
00:34:14,409 --> 00:34:19,170
Rym: And once Napster died, once we knew it was dead forever, all the other ones exploded.

606
00:34:19,989 --> 00:34:21,215
Scott: WinMX came out.

607
00:34:21,597 --> 00:34:22,380
Scott: Kazaa.

608
00:34:22,782 --> 00:34:24,509
Scott: Nutella finally got some users.

609
00:34:25,870 --> 00:34:28,681
Scott: You know, Limewire, which is I think also Nutella.

610
00:34:28,702 --> 00:34:30,690
Scott: It got crazy go nuts.

611
00:34:31,030 --> 00:34:31,110
Rym: Yep.

612
00:34:31,355 --> 00:34:32,228
Rym: Then there was WinMX.

613
00:34:32,670 --> 00:34:32,973
Scott: Oh, wait, wait.

614
00:34:33,114 --> 00:34:33,679
Scott: Hotline.

615
00:34:33,719 --> 00:34:34,790
Scott: Hotline was classic.

616
00:34:35,271 --> 00:34:36,699
Rym: I totally forgot about Hotline, didn't you?

617
00:34:36,759 --> 00:34:38,630
Rym: You ran that Hotline server for a while.

618
00:34:38,851 --> 00:34:39,408
Scott: I sure did.

619
00:34:39,610 --> 00:34:40,330
Rym: It was really popular.

620
00:34:40,630 --> 00:34:42,449
Scott: We got lots of anime on that Hotline server.

621
00:34:42,770 --> 00:34:48,050
Rym: Yeah, we basically, Scott set up a Hotline server at RIT, and we got fansubs and shared them.

622
00:34:48,572 --> 00:34:51,949
Scott: Hotline was actually this really old thing.

623
00:34:52,710 --> 00:35:09,570
Scott: You would run a Hotline server, and people with Hotline clients could visit it, and Hotline servers had files that were shared and rules about sharing the files, and you could upload things to a Hotline server, and you could have a message of the day, and you could chat on the Hotline servers.

624
00:35:09,790 --> 00:35:15,490
Scott: They had all kinds of... It was just a server you could connect to with the Hotline client and do all sorts of things on.

625
00:35:16,590 --> 00:35:22,170
Scott: And mostly, people would go around looking for Hotline servers and download files from them and upload files to them.

626
00:35:22,630 --> 00:35:26,630
Rym: Yep, it was real slick, it was real fun, and it slowly got shot down over time.

627
00:35:26,730 --> 00:35:27,619
Scott: I don't know if it got shut down.

628
00:35:27,639 --> 00:35:28,750
Scott: I think something weird happened to the company.

629
00:35:28,973 --> 00:35:30,190
Rym: Not shut down, shot down.

630
00:35:30,430 --> 00:35:32,201
Scott: Oh, it got something weird happened to the company.

631
00:35:32,222 --> 00:35:33,530
Scott: It was a very strange situation.

