728
00:40:51,259 --> 00:40:56,289
Scott: The torrent file is just a description of where the real file's at and how to get it.

729
00:40:56,932 --> 00:41:00,610
Scott: So you just download this little torrent file, and you run it with Bittorrent client.

730
00:41:01,211 --> 00:41:04,548
Scott: The Bittorrent client looks at the torrent file, and it says, "Okay, that's how I'm going to get this

731
00:41:04,568 --> 00:41:04,849
Scott: file.".

732
00:41:05,371 --> 00:41:12,869
Scott: It goes around to the tracker, and the tracker says, "Okay, these are the people who have that file and are torrenting it right

733
00:41:12,909 --> 00:41:13,090
Scott: now.".

734
00:41:13,511 --> 00:41:20,910
Scott: And then you hook up with all the other people who are torrenting the file that you want, and it starts getting pieces from all those different people at once.

735
00:41:21,650 --> 00:41:30,270
Scott: And as you collect pieces, if new people come around who don't have the pieces that you got, you give them the pieces that you got, and other people give you the pieces you don't got.

736
00:41:30,850 --> 00:41:38,510
Scott: And if there's a whole lot of people doing the same file at once, you can get the whole file pretty quickly, because there's just so many people giving you pieces.

737
00:41:39,230 --> 00:41:42,659
Scott: But if there aren't so many people, then it takes a long time.

738
00:41:42,699 --> 00:41:47,070
Scott: If there's just one guy and you, you just directly download it from him really slowly.

739
00:41:47,710 --> 00:41:52,170
